04178nam a22005535i 9780300130522DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20082008ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001305227 a10.12987/97803001305222doi  a(DE-B1597)485472  a(OCoLC)1024054410  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aLC1011b.H365 2001eb 7aEDU0030002bisacsh04a370.11/22211 aHart, Jeffrey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSmiling Through the Cultural Catastrophe :bToward the Revival of Higher Education /cJeffrey Hart. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b10 b-w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tPART ONE: THE GREAT NARRATIVE -- tChapter One: Athens and Jerusalem -- tChapter Two: Athens: The Heroic Phase -- tChapter Three: Moses as Epic Hero -- tChapter Four: Socrates and Jesus: Internalizing the Heroic -- tChapter Five: Paul: Universal Synthesis -- tPART TWO: EXPLORATIONS -- tChapter Six: Augustine Chooses Jerusalem -- tChapter Seven: Dante, Rome (Athens), Jerusalem, and Amor -- tChapter Eight: Hamlet’s Great Song -- tChapter Nine: The Indispensable Enlightenment: Molière and Voltaire -- tChapter Ten: Hamlet in St. Petersburg, Faust in Great Neck: Dostoyevsky and Scott Fitzgerald -- tAfterword: Today and Tomorrow -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough the essential books of Western civilization are no longer central in our courses or in our thoughts, they retain their ability to energize us intellectually, says Jeffrey Hart in this powerful book. He now presents a guide to some of these literary works, tracing the main currents of Western culture for all who wish to understand the roots of their civilization and the basis for its achievements.Hart focuses on the productive tension between the classical and biblical strains in our civilization--between a life based on cognition and one based on faith and piety. He begins with the Iliad and Exodus, linking Achilles and Moses as Bronze Age heroic figures. Closely analyzing texts and illuminating them in unexpected ways, he moves on to Socrates and Jesus, who “internalized the heroic,” continues with Paul and Augustine and their Christian synthesis, addresses Dante, Shakespeare (Hamlet), Molière, and Voltaire, and concludes with the novel as represented by Crime and Punishment and The Great Gatsby. Hart maintains that the dialectical tensions suggested by this survey account for the restlessness and singular achievements of the West and that the essential books can provide the substance and energy currently missed by both students and educated readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCivilizationxStudy and teaching. 0aEducation, Humanistic. 7aEDUCATION / Aims & Objectives.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030008704840uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030013052240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300130522423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300130522/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY